-- Japanese, Australian Stock Futures Climb on U.S. Consumer Spending Report
-- B y   M o n a m i   Y u i   a n d   S a t o s h i   K a w a n o
-- 2010-10-03T23:29:37Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-03/japanese-australian-stock-futures-climb-on-u-s-consumer-spending-report.html
Japanese and Australian  stock   futures 
rose after increased U.S. consumer spending and confidence
boosted optimism in a global economic recovery.  American depositary receipts of Toyota Motor Corp., a
Japanese carmaker that gets 31 percent of its revenue in North
America, gained 0.3 percent in New York on Oct. 1. Those of BHP
Billiton Ltd., the world’s No. 1 mining company and Australia’s
biggest oil producer, climbed 1.8 percent after crude oil and
metals prices advanced. ADRs of Mitsubishi Corp., Japan’s
largest commodities trader, rose 0.5 percent.  Futures on Japan’s Nikkei 225 Stock Average expiring in
December closed at 9,435 in Chicago on Oct.1, compared with
9,385 in Singapore. They were bid in the pre-market at 9,450 in
Osaka, Japan, at 8:05 a.m. local time. Futures on Australia’s
S&P/ASX 200 Index advanced 0.9 percent today. New Zealand’s NZX
50 Index gained 0.3 percent in Wellington.  “Concern about a double dip is easing,” said  Tomochika Kitaoka , a senior strategist at Mizuho Securities Co. in Tokyo,
referring to the risk of a second recession in three years.  Futures on the  Standard & Poor’s 500 Index  fell 0.3 percent.
The index climbed 0.4 percent on Oct. 1 in New York after
Commerce Department data showed consumer purchases rose 0.4
percent in August, exceeding the 0.3 percent median increase
projected by economists surveyed by Bloomberg News. Incomes
gained 0.5 percent, the biggest advance this year. The Thomson
Reuters/University of Michigan measure of consumer confidence
declined less than forecast, signaling the largest part of the
economy may be stabilizing.  Manufacturing, Fed  Also on Oct. 1, the Arizona-based Institute for Supply
Management said its  factory index  dropped to 54.4 in September
from 56.3 the prior month, showing a slowing pace of expansion
in U.S. manufacturing. The same day, Federal Reserve Bank of New
York President William Dudley said the central bank will
probably need to act to spur the recovery and avert deflation.  The  MSCI Asia Pacific Index  has risen 5.5 percent this year
on speculation growth in corporate profits will weather Europe’s
debt crisis, Chinese steps to curb property-price inflation and
concern about the pace of the U.S. economic rebound. Stocks in
the gauge trade at 14.1 times estimated profit on average,
compared with 13.7 times for the S&P 500 and 11.9 times for the
Stoxx Europe 600 Index  The London Metal Exchange Index of six industrial metals
including copper and zinc rose 1.1 percent on Oct. 1 to its
highest level since April. Oil for November delivery gained 2
percent to settle at $81.58 a barrel in New York after climbing
as high as $81.64, the highest level since Aug. 5.  To contact the reporter on this story:
